## How It Works

When a child process terminates, it enters the zombie state (Z). The kernel cannot fully reclaim the process table entry because the parent must be able to retrieve the child's exit status, resource usage statistics, and termination signal via wait or waitpid. The zombie struct in the kernel's process table is approximately 1.5 KB and holds the PID, exit code, user and system CPU time, memory usage, and the termination signal.

The kernel sends SIGCHLD to the parent when a child exits. If the parent ignores this signal (SIG_DFL) or never calls waitpid, the zombie persists indefinitely. The waitpid function takes three arguments: pid (specific child, -1 for any child), status pointer (where exit code is written), and options (WNOHANG for non-blocking behavior).

The PID table is a finite resource. On Linux, /proc/sys/kernel/pid_max defaults to 32768. When zombies fill the table, fork returns EAGAIN and no new processes can start on the system. This is a hard denial-of-service condition.

## Code Example

```c
#include <sys/wait.h>
#include <signal.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <errno.h>

void handle_sigchld(int sig) {
    int saved_errno = errno;
    while (1) {
        int status;
        pid_t pid = waitpid(-1, &status, WNOHANG);
        if (pid <= 0) break;
        printf("Reaped child PID %d, exit code %d\n",
               pid, WEXITSTATUS(status));
    }
    errno = saved_errno;
}

int main() {
    signal(SIGCHLD, handle_sigchld);

    for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        pid_t pid = fork();
        if (pid == 0) {
            printf("Child %d PID %d exiting\n", i, getpid());
            _exit(i);
        }
    }

    pause();
    return 0;
}
```

Compile and run to see each child reaped immediately. Remove the signal handler then run again while watching ps output in another terminal to observe zombie accumulation.

## Key Points

- **Zombie state is deliberate, not a bug**: The kernel retains process entries because the POSIX wait/waitpid API requires the parent to collect exit status. This is an intentional design choice, not a kernel leak.
- **Zombies consume only PID slots**: No CPU, no memory pages, no file descriptors. The only resource consumed is a PID table entry, but PID exhaustion is a fatal failure mode.
- **SIGCHLD coalescing requires a loop**: The kernel delivers at most one SIGCHLD signal per pending notification. If three children exit before the signal handler runs, only one SIGCHLD is delivered. A single waitpid call drains one zombie. The loop drains all of them.

## Common Mistake

Using wait instead of waitpid in a SIGCHLD handler, or calling waitpid once instead of looping. Developers often write a handler that calls waitpid once, assuming one call per signal. This misses children because SIGCHLD is coalesced by the kernel. If four children exit before the handler runs, only one SIGCHLD is delivered. A single waitpid reaps one child. The remaining three stay as zombies indefinitely. The same problem occurs with wait, which is always blocking when no child has exited and cannot specify WNOHANG in a signal handler context without risking the handler blocking the main process.

## Interview Tip

The interviewer is testing understanding of the process lifecycle as a kernel-level contract, not just a trivia fact. A good answer explains that zombies are the kernel's mechanism for preserving exit status until the parent collects it. A great answer explains SIGCHLD coalescing, the gdb attach technique for emergency reaping without restarting production processes, and the difference between reparenting behavior of PID 1 versus regular processes in containers.
